context: The Teutonic Order lost eastern Prussia when <b3_0>Grand Master <a0_0>Albert of Brandenburg-Ansbach<b3_0/><a0_0/> converted to Lutheranism and secularized the Prussian branch of the Teutonic Order in <a1_0><b5_0><b7_0>1525<b7_0/><b5_0/><a1_0/>. Albert established himself as the <a2_0>first duke of the Duchy of Prussia<a2_0/> and a vassal of the Polish crown by the Prussian Homage. <b6_0>Walter von Cronberg<b6_0/>, the next Grand Master, was enfeoffed with the title to Prussia after the Diet of Augsburg in 1530, but the Order never regained possession of the territory. In <b4_0>1569<b4_0/> the Hohenzollern prince-electors of the Margraviate of Brandenburg became co-regents with Albert's son, the feeble-minded Albert Frederick.
